properties.name: Okame
properties.notes: An early bloomer, the okame peaks before the Yoshinos. Its uniqueness in the park and bright pink blooms make it a special treat.

properties.name: Autumn-flowering
properties.notes: Autumn-flowering cherry trees can bloom at any time of year, including fall and during warm spells in winter. Look for smaller, less showy blossoms.

properties.name: Weeping
properties.notes: The weeping cherry tree is easily identified by its long, drooping branches. They are found throughout the park.

properties.name: Takesimensis
properties.notes: The Takesimensis tree was planted here because it was expected to better tolerate this flood-prone area. Look for shorter, stubbier twigs compared to other cherry varieties.

properties.name: Usuzumi
properties.notes: Some Usuzumis in Japan are over 1,500 years old. They have survived that long because of plenty of care.

properties.name: Yoshino
properties.notes: Perhaps the most famous and archetypal cherry tree in D.C., the Somei Yoshino is the most common cherry tree in the park.

properties.name: Akebono
properties.notes: The Akebono is a variant of the more common Yoshino cherry tree.

properties.name: Shirofugen
properties.notes: The Shirofugen tree blooms later than most cherry trees. If you missed the peak of the Yoshinos, try this area!

properties.name: Fugenzo
properties.notes: Fugenzo trees are a great example of how cherry trees are grafted, and are easily distinguished by their thick, straight trunks.

properties.name: Afterglow
properties.notes: Look for this early bloomer to peak ahead of the Yoshino blossoms.

properties.name: Sargent
properties.notes: Sargent trees are planted individually, scattered throughout the park. They are easy to distinguish from surrounding cherry varieties by their deep pink colored flowers.

properties.name: Kwanzan
properties.notes: A popular tree for landscaping, Kwanzan trees bloom 10-14 days after the Yoshinos, and produce large, dense flowers.
